  }), "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZBzzO6kHUGM")), mdx("p", null, "Outros"), mdx("p", null, "Worms work great for micro fishing. \xA0Many micro fish have very small mouths so the smallest piece of worm you can get on the hook is ideal. \xA0Using your finger nail, or clippers, will be your best options for preparing the bait. \xA0Maggots, blood worms, and gluten also work for micro fishing. \xA0When necessity dictates, a wide variety of other food sources can also work as bait for catching minnows. Some good baits you can purchase at the grocery store are bread, cheese, and imitation crab.\nThe depth of the bait in the water is important and will determine what species of fish you will catch. \xA0If the bait is teased on the surface of the water you will attract aggressive topminnows and other species that primarily feed at this level. \xA0Letting the bait fall to the bed of the pool or stream will entice benthic feeders such as darters and madtom. Time of day, swiftness of current, structures, and substrate are also factors to consider when targeting micro fish. \xA0Researching habitats and feeding traits of fish will increase your chances of landing the right species."), mdx("p", null, "Microfishing photo tank\n", mdx("a", _extends({
